Semilarski vs. Prosecutor's office: the cassation of the former vice-mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances refused to consider the claim of Semilarsky, but in April his cassation appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On December 12, 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, since its permission is not within its competence of the administrative court.
The court's decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for damage caused during criminal proceedings.
"The prosecutor's office and the county court should regulate such issues," Anett Kreitsmann, spokesman for the Tartu Courts, told ERR.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the state court will have to say his word.
According to defender Semilarski, sworn lawyer Oliver Nyaes, his client was unreasonably under suspicion of bribery for about two years.
Now he demands from the prosecutor's office to refute the wrong allegations in his address and to compensate him for moral damage.
The reason for filing a complaint to the court was the statements of the prosecutor for special cases of the Lyuna district prosecutor's office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, along with the other at the time, Vice-Mayor Tartu Artem Suvorov was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
"Recall that when I was detained, the Security Police and the prosecutor's office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu, one of the most influential local governments, are corrupt.
These public suspicions hanging in the air have accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions have turned out to be false, the prosecutor's office does not want to say anything about it," - commented Semilarski in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyaes, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor's office should operate.
"The claim of bribery and corruption turned out to be false, but that's not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as in Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, representatives of the state should be careful when choosing words so that the suspects would not be represented as criminals before the sentencing.
To this prosecutor's office is obliged by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not respected in this case against Valvo Semilarski," - said Nyase.
"Semilarsky's public submission as a serious offender and bribe-taker in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being clarified is inadmissible, which is contrary to the presumption of innocence and unfair to the applicant," he added.
As rus.err.ee wrote, former vice-mayor of Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be prosecuted on charges of bribery - the criminal case against him in July was partially closed.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of deliberate violation of anti-corruption legislation in transactions in particularly large amounts.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu more than thirty times participated in meetings of the city administration when making decisions related to the companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or leaders of which Semilarsky actively communicated at the personal level in off-ended hours.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarsky had personal interests, and therefore he had to withdraw from participation in decision-making.
Earlier, as wrote rus.err.ee, the prosecutor's office presented Semilarski suspicions of receiving a bribe and violation of anti-corruption legislation during transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
Then the prosecutor's office and the security police said that there is good evidence against both vice-mayors.
Both officials then resigned.
The case of Suvorov later reached the court, which fully justified the politician.
The trial in the Valvo Semilarsky case is still ongoing.
