How will the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate on the economy will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia has expectedly again lowered the key rate.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage points, to 4.25% per annum - formally another historical minimum.
Judging by the return of a short rate of rate cuts, as well as the tone of the Central Bank's statements and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at economic prospects more optimistic than before.
This means that the current monetary easing cycle may soon stop.
"We continued to ease monetary policy, primarily given that there are still risks of inflation from 4% in 2021," said Elvira Nabiullina, head of the Bank of Russia.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a fall in domestic and external demand.
The recovery of the economy, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes have revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and production of consumer goods were expanding, the annual rate of decline in freight turnover, industrial production slowed down.
According to the updated forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the economy will be 4.5-5.5% (before that was expected 4-6%), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised the forecast for annual oil prices to $ 38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Previously, the Central Bank expected $27 and $35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia's forecast for inflation for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The view of the Bank of Russia on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the easing cycle, according to economists in Russia and the CIS "Renaissance Capital" Sofia Donets and Andrei Melashchenko.
So, the Bank of Russia has consistently reduced the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it by one percentage point at once due to low inflation rates due to the suppressed demand and the need to stimulate the stalling of the economy that has stalled due to the pandemic and associated restrictions.
The chances for the adjustment of monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees the chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The combination of pro-inflationary risks also indicates the proximity of pauses in easing interest rate policies - disrupted supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures, and faster (comparedly expected) recovery in demand, he says.
To top the next actions of the Bank of Russia will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, said Koshelev.
One way or another, the reduction of the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, possibly, on a mortgage, says senior economist of the analytical management of Otkritie Bank Maxim Petronevich.
The rate correction will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he clarifies.
Bets on consumer loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude the economist of BCS Premier Anton Pokatovich.
The average rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they may fall to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
Then they can drop to 4%, if the Central Bank reduces the key rate in the fall, says Pokatovich.
